    % Set up a column 
    \begin{column}{.49\textwidth}
      \begin{beamercolorbox}[center,wd=\textwidth]{postercolumn}
        \begin{minipage}[T]{.95\textwidth}  % tweaks the width, makes a new \textwidth
          \parbox[t][\columnheight]{\textwidth}{ % must be some better way to set the the height, width and textwidth simultaneously
            % Since all columns are the same length, it is all nice and tidy.  You have to get the height empirically
            % ---------------------------------------------------------%
            % fill each column with content            
            \begin{block}{{\Large Introduction}}
              \justifying
              {\large              
                {\bf
                  Large-scale spiral structures have been observed in
                  the outer parts of transition disks. These could be
                  due to unseen planets, but theoretical alternatives
                  should be explored. We describe a 
                  new but simple mechanism that can lead to the growth
                  of one-armed spirals, or eccentric modes, in irradiated 
                  astrophysical disks, which may be applicable to the outer
                  parts of protoplanetary disks. We explain this new
                  instability with linear density wave 
                  theory, confirm it through 2D and 3D
                  hydrodynamic simulations, and find that  this mechanism can
                  produce long-lived spiral structures. 
                }
              }
            \end{block}
            \vfill
            
             \begin{block}{{\Large The locally isothermal disk}}
              \justifying
              In the outer parts of protoplanetary disks, thermal
              timescales can be short due to stellar
              irradiation. Theoretical modeling then simplifies
              significantly by adopting the \emph{locally isothermal
                disk}, in which the disk temperature is prescribed as
              a function of position, e.g., 
              \begin{align*}
                T(r) = T_0\left(\frac{r}{r_0}\right)^{-q} \quad\text{or}\quad c_s^2(r)
                = c_{s0}^2\left(\frac{r}{r_0}\right)^{-q}.
              \end{align*}
              In fact, locally isothermal disks are widely used in 
              numerical simulations. Because no energy equation is 
              explicitly solved, this reduces computational costs
              tremendously. However, this leads to new effects when
              considering how small disturbances in the disk evolve. 
            \end{block}
            \vfill
            
            \begin{block}{{\Large Non-conservation of angular momentum
                }}
              \justifying
              \begin{itemize}
              \item Consider linear perturbations to the disk, e.g.
                \begin{align*}
                  \Sigma(r,\phi, t) \to \Sigma(r) + \delta\Sigma(r)\exp{\left[\mathrm{i}\left(m\phi-\sigma t\right)\right]} 
                \end{align*}
                etc., $\sigma$: frequency, $m$: azimuthal wavenumber.
              \item Non-axisymmetric disturbances ($m\neq0$) in a rotating disk
                satisfy angular momentum conservation,
              \end{itemize}
                \begin{align*}
                  \frac{\p J_\mathrm{pert}}{\p t} + \nabla\cdot
                  \bm{F}_\mathrm{pert} = \begin{cases}
                    0 & \text{barotropic/adiabatic}\\
                    -\frac{m}{2}\imag\left(\delta\Sigma\xi_r^*\frac{dc_s^2}{dr}\right)
                    & \text{locally isothermal 2D}\\
                    \frac{m}{2}\imag\left[\rho\left(\nabla\cdot\bm{\xi}\right)\bm{\xi}^*\cdot\nabla
                      c_s^2\right] 
                    & \text{locally isothermal 3D.}
                  \end{cases}
                \end{align*}
                \begin{itemize}
	       \item $\bm{\xi}$: Lagrangian displacement.
               \item Locally isothermal disk:  $J_\mathrm{pert}$ can
                 change due to temperature gradient.
               \item \textcolor{blue}{{\bf SMALL DISTURBANCES DO NOT CONSERVE THEIR
                   ANGULAR MOMENTUM IN LOCALLY ISOTHERMAL DISKS!}}
             \item Exchange of angular momentum between small disturbances
               and the background disk $\to$ \textcolor{blue}{{\bf POSSIBLE
                 INSTABILITY}}! 
             \item Estimate of growth rate for low frequency
               disturbances:
               \begin{align*}
                 \gamma \sim \frac{1}{2}q
                 \left(\frac{H}{r}\right)\left(\frac{k_rH}{m}\right)\Omega. 
               \end{align*}
             \item $H$: disk scale height, $\Omega$: disk rotation, $k_r$: radial wavenumber.
              \end{itemize}
            \end{block}
            \vfill
            
            \begin{block}{{\Large Numerical demonstration}}
              \justifying
              Example: radially structured, self-gravitating disk,
              fixed temperature profile: 
              \begin{figure}
                \subfloat[][Surface density]{
                  \centering
                  \includegraphics[scale=0.95,clip=true,
                  trim=0.6cm 0cm 0cm 0cm]{compare_profiles_dens000}}
                \subfloat[][Toomre parameter]{
                  \centering
                  \includegraphics[scale=0.95,clip=true,
                  trim=0.8cm 0cm 0cm 0cm]{compare_profiles_Q000}}
               \end{figure}
               \begin{itemize}
               \item Radial structure `traps' low frequency  $m=1$ modes ($|\sigma|\ll\Omega$).
               \item \textcolor{blue}{Temperature gradient then destabilizes them.}
               \end{itemize}
               Codes: 
               \begin{itemize}
               \item {\bf FARGO}: 2D cylindrical, finite difference,
                 Poisson via FFT.
               \item {\bf ZEUS-MP}: 3D spherical, finite difference,
                 Poisson via linear solver. 
               \item {\bf PLUTO}: 3D spherical,
                 Godunov, Poisson via spherical harmonics.
               \end{itemize}
               
            \end{block}
            \vfill
